<br>
A NASA scientist has proposed a new theory that explains the &quot;great bombardment&quot; that pocked the moon and may have delivered the elements of life to Earth about 3.9 billion years ago.<br>
<br>
What Dr. John Chambers, NASA Ames Research Center, proposed to the Lunar and Planetary Science conference in Houston recently, was that there may have been a tenth planet in the solar system and that planet disintegrated sending a bombardment of asteroids at the Earth and Moon.<br>
<br>
Chambers called it Planet V and suggested it would have orbited between Mars and the asteroid belt. In this position it would have survived only about 600 million years until the force of Mars sent it spinning into the belt. <br>
<br>
There it could have propelled enough asteroids toward Earth to create the effects of the bombardment. According the Chambers, once Planet V, which he estimated to be about a 10th the size of Mars, had gone into the asteroid belt, the tremendous gravity of Jupiter would have cast it back until it plunged to its destruction in the Sun. <br>
<br>
The theory takes a step toward explaining how such a large bombardment of objects could occur and then stop. Several theories have been proposed for the phenomenon, including remnants of the formation of Uranus and Neptune. Scientists know about when it occurred from the dating of rocks taken from the moon. <br>
<br>
